<!-- INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01 — About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">Most dryer repairs are straightforward. The vent usually isn't.</h2>

        <p>Dryers fail in predictable ways. A thermal fuse blows and the heat stops. A drum belt snaps and the drum won't turn. The door switch fails and the machine won't start. The idler pulley wears out and it starts squealing. Our technicians carry these parts on the van for the brands they see most across SoCal — Samsung, LG, Whirlpool, Miele, Bosch, Speed Queen — and can complete most repairs the same visit.</p>

        <p>What's less predictable is the vent. A clogged dryer vent is one of the leading causes of house fires in the US, and across SoCal — from West Hollywood high-rise stacked closets to Newport Beach laundry alcoves to Thousand Oaks utility rooms with long flex runs to Riverside County mobile-home installations — the failure modes vary, but lint buildup is universal. Lint accumulates faster in a short, kinked duct. The dryer runs hotter. The thermal fuse trips. And the symptom that sends people our way — clothes not drying properly, or taking two cycles — is usually the vent, not the dryer itself.</p>

        <p>We include a dryer vent inspection on every repair call across all 5 counties. Not a visual glance — an actual airflow check. If the vent needs cleaning, we do it. If the duct is kinked or damaged, we tell you before we leave.</p>

        <div class="tip-safety">
          <div class="tip-label">🔥 Fire Safety — Read This</div>
          <p>According to NFPA data, dryers cause roughly 16,000 home fires annually in the US — and lint buildup is the cause in the majority of those. In SoCal condos and apartments where the dryer vents through a closet wall or a long flexible duct, annual vent cleaning isn't optional. It's the difference between a dryer that works and one that becomes a hazard. We offer standalone dryer vent cleaning if you just need that service — call and ask.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="tip-box">
          <div class="tip-label">⏱ Clothes Taking Too Long?</div>
          <p>If your dryer takes two or three cycles to dry a normal load, the dryer itself is probably fine. Check the lint screen first — it should be cleared before every load. If that's clean, the vent duct is almost certainly the issue. A partially clogged vent restricts airflow and cuts drying efficiency dramatically. We see this constantly across SoCal apartments and condos.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="diy-box">
          <div class="diy-label">🔧 Before You Call — 5 Quick Checks</div>
          <h3>Try these in 15 minutes — they fix maybe 30% of "no heat" / "takes too long" calls before we even dispatch.</h3>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Clean the lint screen — every load.</strong> Most "won't dry" calls trace back here. If you can't see through the screen, that's your problem.</li>
            <li><strong>Deep-clean the lint trap quarterly.</strong> Pull the screen out, vacuum the slot. A surprising amount of lint gets past the screen and accumulates in the housing.</li>
            <li><strong>Check the exterior vent flap.</strong> Should open easily when the dryer runs. Stuck flaps mean buildup at the cap or in the duct.</li>
            <li><strong>Inspect the flex duct behind the dryer.</strong> Look for kinks, crushing, disconnections. Replace damaged flex with rigid aluminum if you can.</li>
            <li><strong>Level the machine.</strong> Excessive vibration usually means a leg loosened or the machine walked. Adjust feet, lock the nuts; bubble level should sit dead center.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>

