<!-- RECENT REPAIRS — 2 LA + 1 OC + 1 Ventura -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">West Hollywood (LA County) · LG Gas Dryer</div>
        <h3>"Starts, heats for a few minutes, then goes cold mid-cycle"</h3>
        <p>Textbook gas valve coil failure on an LG gas dryer. The igniter was intact and the initial flame lit — but the secondary gas valve coil had failed, so once the igniter cooled down the valve closed and the heat stopped. This gets misdiagnosed as a thermal fuse more often than it should. A multimeter test on the coils makes it clear.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced all three gas valve solenoid coils (replacing just the failed one leaves the others about to fail — we replace the set). OEM LG parts. Full heat cycle confirmed before closing out. Total time: 1 hour including diagnosis.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Pasadena (LA County) · Miele T1 Heat Pump Dryer</div>
        <h3>"Squealing noise getting louder every week"</h3>
        <p>Worn drum bearing on a Miele T1 — these are condensation dryers with a heat pump, no external vent required, which is why they're popular in renovated Pasadena craftsmans where running a new duct isn't feasible. The drum bearing wear was gradual but had reached the point where it was audible from the next room.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced drum bearing assembly with OEM Miele parts sourced from authorized distributor. Miele T1 disassembly is more involved than a standard vented dryer — took about 90 minutes. Machine running quietly, heat pump function verified. Customer also asked about the condenser filter — hadn't been cleaned in two years. Cleaned that as well.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (Orange County) · Samsung Electric Stackable</div>
        <h3>"Dryer runs but no heat — been like this for a week"</h3>
        <p>Blown thermal fuse — classic presentation on a Samsung electric stackable. Customer had been re-running loads twice hoping it would fix itself. The fuse was the symptom; the vent was the cause. The dryer was in a hall closet with a 12-foot flexible duct run that had partially collapsed behind the drywall shelf above the washer.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced thermal fuse with OEM Samsung part. Pulled machine out, found duct compressed at a 90-degree bend. Replaced flexible section with rigid aluminum elbow. Confirmed airflow at exterior vent before leaving. Customer noted the dryer runs faster than it ever had.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura County) · Whirlpool Electric</div>
        <h3>"Loud banging sound on every rotation"</h3>
        <p>Worn drum rollers — on this Whirlpool the rear drum support rollers had worn flat on one side, creating a thumping impact with each rotation. Common on a dryer that's run for 8+ years without the rollers being replaced. Technically it'll keep running for a while, but the flat spot gets worse and eventually the roller disintegrates into the drum.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced both rear drum rollers and the front drum glides (they were original and worn). Also replaced drum belt — it was cracked and would have been the next call. OEM Whirlpool parts throughout. Customer appreciated knowing all three issues were addressed at once rather than two separate service calls.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

