<!-- REPAIR VS REPLACE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">09 — Repair or Replace?</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">When does it make sense to fix it vs buy new?</h2>
    <p class="lead">A $700 vented dryer with a $400 control board is borderline. A $4,000 Miele T1 heat pump with a $400 sensor is an obvious repair. Here's the rubric our technicians actually use.</p>

    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card">
        <span class="rvr-verdict repair">Almost always repair</span>
        <h3>Miele · Bosch · Thermador · Electrolux Pro · Speed Queen</h3>
        <p>Built for 15-20+ year service lives. Replacement runs $1,800-$5,000+. Even a $700 control board on a 12-year-old Miele T1 is the right call — drum, bearings, motor, heat pump module all have another decade in them.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Heat pump module replacement: yes, even at $700-$1,200</li>
          <li>Drum bearing / glides: always worth it</li>
          <li>Door gasket / sensor: always worth it</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card">
        <span class="rvr-verdict judge">Judgment call — use the rule</span>
        <h3>Samsung · LG · Whirlpool · Maytag · GE · Frigidaire</h3>
        <p>Mid-market vented dryers have an honest 8-12 year design life. Past that, parts are still available but the rest of the unit is aging in parallel.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Under 8 years AND repair under $300 → repair</li>
          <li>Over 10 years AND repair over $400 → consider replacing</li>
          <li>Drum or motor failure on 10+ year unit → strongly consider replacing</li>
          <li>Multiple failures in one visit → almost always replace</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

